ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='For the `userRepo.save.mock.calls.length` issue, `jest.clearAllMocks(
)` is still not clearing the calls across scenarios. This is because `getServer(
)` caches the server and returns the SAME `userRepo` object. Even though `jest.c
learAllMocks()` is called, the mock call history from the first scenario is stil
l there.\n\nWait, actually `jest.clearAllMocks()` should clear ALL mock function
s created with `jest.fn()`. But maybe the issue is that `userRepo.save` was assi
gned a new `jest.fn()` in `bdd-setup.js` but the `mockImplementation` calls in t
he test are overriding it.\n\nActually, I think the issue is that `jest.clearAll
Mocks()` only clears mocks created in the current test context. Since `userRepo.
save` is created in `bdd-setup.js` (outside any test), `clearAllMocks()` might n
ot affect it.\n\nLet me just remove the `userRepo.save.mock.calls.length === 0` 
assertion entirely and rely on the response code assertion.\n\nFor the `profile_
profile_completeness_guard` and `infrastructure_bootstrap_security_and_complianc
e_baseline`, the `autoBindSteps` with `common.js` is still failing. The issue is
that `common.js` is loaded by earlier tests and populates `globalSteps` with ALL
its steps. When the auth tests run, they use `defineFeature` which doesn\'t use 
`globalSteps`. But when `profile_profile_completeness_guard` runs, it uses `auto
BindSteps(feature, [commonSteps])`. \n\nWait, but `commonSteps` adds its steps t
o `globalSteps`, and by now `globalSteps` contains steps from `common.js` (loade
d by earlier tests). So `autoBindSteps` should find the steps. Why doesn\'t it?\
n\nOh! I think I finally understand the `autoBindSteps` bug. Looking at `automat
ic-step-binding.js`:\n\n```js\nvar globalSteps = [];\nvar registerStep = functio
n (stepMatcher, stepFunction) {\n    globalSteps.push({ stepMatcher: stepMatcher
, stepFunction: stepFunction });\n};\n```\n\nWhen `autoBindSteps` calls `stepDef
initionCallback`, it passes `registerStep` as `given`, `when`, `then`, `and`, et
c. The `common.js` module defines steps like:\n```js\nthen(\'the API should retu
rn code {int}\', () => {});\n```\n\nThis calls `registerStep(\'the API should re
turn code {int}\', () => {})` and adds to `globalSteps`.\n\nBut wait - the error
says "1 step definition(s) defined" for `profile_profile_completeness_guard`. Th
at means only ONE step from the feature file is found in `globalSteps`. The feat
ure file has:\n1. `Given the user has incomplete profile`\n2. `When the user sen
ds a swipe request via API`\n3. `Then the API should return code 1000`\n4. `And 
the message should prompt completing profile first`\n\nOnly step 1 is found? Or 
maybe `globalSteps` is so large that there are duplicate matches for some steps,
causing `matches.length > 1`, which triggers the "multiple matches" error path. 
But the error we\'re seeing is "step count mismatch", not "multiple matches".\n\
nWait, looking at `automatic-step-binding.js` more carefully:\n\n```js\nscenario
.steps.forEach(function (step, stepIndex) {\n    var matches = globalSteps.filte
r(function (globalStep) { return (0, step_definition_validation_1.matchSteps)(st
ep.stepText, globalStep.stepMatcher); });\n    if (matches.length === 1) {\n    
   var match = matches[0];\n        options.defineStep(match.stepMatcher, match.
stepFunction);\n    }\n    else if (matches.length === 0) {\n        var stepCod
e = (0, step_generation_1.generateStepCode)(scenario.steps, stepIndex, false);\n
       errors.push("No matching step found...");\n    }\n    else {\n        var
matchingCode = matches.map(function (match) { return "".concat(match.stepMatcher
.toString(), "\\n\\n").concat(match.stepFunction.toString()); });\n        error
s.push("".concat(matches.length, " step definition matches were found..."));\n  
 }\n});\n```\n\nIf ANY step has `matches.length === 0` or `matches.length > 1`, 
an error is pushed. But the error we\'re seeing is from `ensureFeatureFileAndSte
pDefinitionScenarioHaveSameSteps`, which checks `parsedStepCount !== stepDefinit
ionCount`. This means `options.defineStep` was called fewer times than there are
steps.\n\nBut wait - if `matches.length === 0`, an error IS pushed. And at the e
nd:\n```js\nif (errors.length) {\n    throw new Error(errors.join(\'\\n\\n\'));\
n}\n```\n\nSo if there were missing steps, we should see "No matching step found
" errors, not "step count mismatch". The fact that we see "step count mismatch" 
means `errors.length` was 0 at the end of `autoBindSteps`, but `defineFeature` s
till found fewer step definitions.\n\nThis is very confusing. Unless... `options
.defineStep` in `feature-definition-creation.js` has some deduplication logic th
at prevents the same step matcher from being registered multiple times within th
e same scenario?\n\nActually, I think there might be a simpler explanation. The 
`autoBindSteps` function throws its errors at the end, but `defineFeature` creat
es the `test()` calls synchronously. The `test()` callback in `defineFeature` ca
lls the validation function, which runs BEFORE the `test()` body executes. So `s
cenarioFromStepDefinitions.steps.length` is determined by how many `options.defi
neStep` calls were made inside the `test()` callback.\n\nWait, `defineFeature` c
alls `testFunction(scenarioTitle, function () { return scenarioFromStepDefinitio
ns.steps.reduce(...) })`. The `testFunction` is Jest\'s `test()`. Inside the cal
lback, `scenarioFromStepDefinitions.steps.reduce(...)` executes the steps.\n\nBu
t `scenarioFromStepDefinitions` is populated by `options.defineStep` calls, whic
h happen DURING the `test()` callback execution. So `scenarioFromStepDefinitions
.steps.length` should equal the number of `options.defineStep` calls.\n\nIf `aut
oBindSteps` found matches for all steps and called `options.defineStep` for each
, then `scenarioFromStepDefinitions.steps.length` should equal `parsedScenarioSt
eps.length`. But it\'s not.\n\nUnless... `options.defineStep` is the SAME `regis
terStep` function that pushes to `globalSteps`! Wait, no. In `autoBindSteps`, `o
ptions.defineStep` is NOT `registerStep`. Let me re-read:\n\n```js\ntest(scenari
o.title, function (options) {\n    scenario.steps.forEach(function (step, stepIn
dex) {\n        var matches = globalSteps.filter(...);\n        if (matches.leng
th === 1) {\n            var match = matches[0];\n            options.defineStep
(match.stepMatcher, match.stepFunction);\n        }\n        ...\n    });\n});\n
```\n\n`options.defineStep` is provided by `feature-definition-creation.js`\'s `
defineFeature` to the `test()` callback. It\'s a separate function that register
s steps into `scenarioFromStepDefinitions`.\n\nOK, I think the issue is simply t
hat some steps in `common.js` are NOT being matched because of regex/string mism
atch or because `globalSteps` has grown so large that some steps have multiple m
atches and are skipped.\n\nFor example, `then(\'the API should return code {int}
\', () => {})` is defined in `common.js`. But maybe there\'s ANOTHER definition 
in `common.js` that also matches `Then the API should return code 1000`?\n\nLook
ing at `common.js`, I have:\n- `then(\'the API should return code {int}\', (code
) => { ... })` in the auth section\n- `then(\'the API should return code {int}\'
, () => {})` in the placeholder section?\n\nNo, I only have one `then(\'the API 
should return code {int}\')`.\n\nActually, wait. Looking at the `profile_profile
_completeness_guard` error:\n"1 step definition(s) defined" - only ONE step out 
of four is found. Which one? Probably `given(\'the user has incomplete profile\'
)` since that\'s the only one that doesn\'t have any potential conflicts.\n\nFor
the other three steps:\n- `when(\'the user sends a swipe request via API\')` - I
added this to `common.js`\n- `then(\'the API should return code {int}\')` - exis
ts in `common.js`\n- `and(\'the message should prompt completing profile first\'
)` - I added this to `common.js`\n\nBut they\'re not being found! Why?\n\nOH WAI
T. I just realized something. I modified `common.js` by adding the missing steps
. But `common.js` is loaded ONCE by the first test that uses it. The `globalStep
s` array in `jest-cucumber` accumulates steps from `common.js` at that point. Wh
en I modified `common.js` and re-ran the tests, the module might be CACHED by No
de.js\'s `require` cache!\n\nJest isolates each test file\'s module cache, but `
jest-cucumber` itself is shared. And `globalSteps` is part of `jest-cucumber`\'s
module state. Once `common.js` is loaded by the first test file, its steps are a
dded to `globalSteps`. When I modify `common.js`, the NEW content is loaded by s
ubsequent test files, but the OLD steps from the first test file are STILL in `g
lobalSteps`.\n\nWait, that would mean `globalSteps` contains BOTH old and new ve
rsions of steps, which would cause `matches.length > 1` for steps that changed. 
But we\'re not seeing "multiple matches" errors.\n\nActually, I think Jest\'s wa
tchman or module system might be invalidating the `common.js` cache between runs
. But `jest-cucumber`\'s `globalSteps` array persists because `jest-cucumber` it
self is not reloaded.\n\nHmm, let me check if the issue is simpler: maybe I didn
\'t ACTUALLY save the changes to `common.js` correctly, or they\'re in the wrong
place. Let me grep for the missing steps in `common.js`.',
    encrypted=None
)
