ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="The BDD tests fail because `ioredis` cannot be found from `bdd-setup.
js`. The jest config runs from `apps/api` but `bdd-setup.js` is in `tests/bdd/st
ep-definitions/`. The module resolution for `ioredis` doesn't work because `test
s/bdd/step-definitions/` is not inside `apps/api` where `ioredis` is installed.\
n\nI need to either:\n1. Move `bdd-setup.js` to `apps/api/` or adjust the module
path\n2. Use a relative path to `ioredis` from `apps/api/node_modules/ioredis`\n
3. Remove the `jest.mock('ioredis')` from `bdd-setup.js` and instead mock it dif
ferently\n\nActually, `jest.mock` resolves modules relative to the test file. Si
nce the test files (`.steps.js`) are imported from `tests/bdd/step-definitions/`
, and `bdd-setup.js` is in the same directory, Jest tries to resolve `ioredis` f
rom `tests/bdd/step-definitions/` which doesn't have `node_modules`.\n\nI can fi
x this by using an absolute or relative path to the actual `ioredis` module. In 
Jest, you can mock a module by its resolved path. But `jest.mock` requires the m
odule to be resolvable.\n\nA simpler fix: instead of mocking `ioredis` in `bdd-s
etup.js`, I can mock the `redisConfig` or inject a mock Redis instance directly.
But `AuthService` creates `new Redis(redisConfig)` inside its constructor.\n\nAc
tually, looking at the auth service test, the `jest.mock('ioredis')` works becau
se the test file is inside `apps/api/src/...` where `ioredis` is resolvable from
`apps/api/node_modules`.\n\nFor BDD tests, I can change `bdd-setup.js` to set th
e module paths correctly. Or, I can update the jest config to add `moduleDirecto
ries` that includes `apps/api/node_modules`.\n\nLet me update the BDD jest confi
g to include the API's node_modules in the module resolution paths.",
    encrypted=None
)
