ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='There are two categories of failures:\n1. `jest-cucumber` still says 
some scenarios have fewer step definitions than expected. This is because `and` 
patterns are not matching correctly. The `and` function in `jest-cucumber` might
be case-sensitive or the pattern matching is different. Looking at the error, fo
r example:\n   - `auth_login_token_refresh` has `then(\'a new access_token and r
efresh_token pair should be returned\')` and `and(\'the old refresh_token should
be invalidated\')` and `and(\'the response code should be {int}\')`.\n   - The `
then` for `response code` exists but as `then(\'the response code should be {int
}\')`. The `and` version I added uses `/^the response code should be (\\d+)$/`. 
Wait, that should match...\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `jest-cucumber
`, when a step in a feature file is `And the response code should be 0`, the lib
rary looks for an `and` step definition with the exact text pattern (minus the p
arameter value). The regex `/^the response code should be (\\d+)$/` should match
. But wait - the `{int}` in the feature file is converted to a regex pattern by 
`jest-cucumber`? No, actually the step definition text in the feature file is `A
nd the response code should be 0`, and `jest-cucumber` uses the step pattern fro
m the Gherkin step text, not the `{int}` placeholder. But `jest-cucumber` might 
normalize `{int}` to `(\\d+)` or something else.\n\nActually, looking at the `Gi
ven/When/Then` functions in `jest-cucumber`, they accept the step text with plac
eholders like `{string}` and `{int}` and convert them to regex automatically. Bu
t I\'m using raw regex in `and()`. That might not work the same way.\n\nWait, th
e `then(\'the response code should be {int}\')` in my `common.js` is using the `
jest-cucumber` API which handles `{int}` placeholders. But my `and(/^the respons
e code should be (\\d+)$/)` uses a raw regex. This should still work because `je
st-cucumber` should match regex patterns too.\n\nBut looking at the error messag
es, `jest-cucumber` says "4 step definition(s) defined" for `auth_login_token_re
fresh`. The step definitions it found are:\n- `given(\'the user has a valid refr
esh_token\')`\n- `when(\'the app calls POST /auth/refresh with the refresh_token
\')`\n- `then(\'a new access_token and refresh_token pair should be returned\')`
\n- `and(\'the old refresh_token should be invalidated\')` - maybe this one is N
OT found\n\nWait, it says 4 step definitions defined but the scenario has 5 step
s. That means ONE of the `and` steps is not matching. Looking at the error outpu
t, it shows the missing step as `and(/^the response code should be (\\d+)$/)`. S
o the `and(\'the old refresh_token should be invalidated\')` might actually be m
atched, but the `and(\'the response code should be {int}\')` is not.\n\nActually
wait - in `common.js` I defined `and(\'the response code should be {int}\')` usi
ng a regex `/^... (\\d+)$/`. But `jest-cucumber` might expect the placeholder sy
ntax like `{int}` for its internal pattern matching, not a raw regex.\n\nLet me 
check how the `then(\'the response code should be {int}\')` is defined. Looking 
at my `common.js`:\n```js\nthen(\'the response code should be {int}\', (code) =>
{ ... });\n```\n\nAnd my `and` alias:\n```js\nand(/^the response code should be 
(\\d+)$/, (code) => { ... });\n```\n\nThe `jest-cucumber` `and` function should 
accept regex. But maybe the issue is that the regex needs to match the exact ste
p text without considering the parameter substitution. Let me try using `{int}` 
in the `and` definition instead of regex.\n\nActually, `jest-cucumber` docs show
that you can pass regex or string patterns. If I pass `{int}` as a string, it sh
ould work the same as `then`. Let me change all the `and` patterns to use the sa
me placeholder syntax as the corresponding `given/when/then` patterns.\n\nLet me
update the `and` definitions:\n- `and(\'the response code should be {int}\', ...
)` instead of regex\n- `and(\'Device A should receive {int} on the next token re
fresh attempt\', ...)`\n- etc.\n\nFor the `auth_login_user_logout` error: `serve
r.post is not a function`. This means `getServer()` is returning something that 
doesn\'t have `.post()`. Looking at `bdd-setup.js`, `server = app.getHttpServer(
)` which should return a function that `supertest` wraps. But wait, I\'m returni
ng `{ server, mockRedis: mockRedisMethods }` from `getServer()`, and in `common.
js` I\'m doing `const { server } = await getServer();` and then `server.post(...
)`.\n\nBut `app.getHttpServer()` returns an HTTP server instance (from Node.js `
http` module), not a supertest agent. In the original `bdd-setup.js`, I intended
to use `supertest` but never actually wrapped the server with it!\n\nI need to u
pdate `bdd-setup.js` to return a supertest agent: `request(server)` instead of `
server`.\n\nLet me fix both issues.',
    encrypted=None
)
