ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Still only 3 step definitions found. This is extremely frustrating. L
et me take a completely different approach - instead of using `autoBindSteps` wi
th `common.js`, I\'ll create dedicated `.steps.js` files for each auth feature t
hat contain all the step definitions inline, without relying on `common.js` for 
auth steps.\n\nActually, looking at the problem more carefully, maybe `common.js
` is just too large and `jest-cucumber` has some internal limitation or conflict
. Or maybe the `autoBindSteps` function has a bug where it can\'t find steps in 
large modules.\n\nLet me check the `jest-cucumber` source to understand how `aut
oBindSteps` works... but that\'s too time-consuming.\n\nA simpler solution: I\'l
l create dedicated step definition files for the auth features and NOT use `comm
on.js` for auth. The existing `.steps.js` files can import `common.js` for share
d steps but define their own auth steps.\n\nActually, the current `.steps.js` fi
les just do `autoBindSteps(feature, [commonSteps])`. I can change them to define
auth steps locally and use `commonSteps` only for non-auth steps.\n\nBut wait - 
the `common.js` module exports ALL steps including auth. If I create local auth 
steps, there might be conflicts.\n\nOK, let me try yet another approach. What if
I split `common.js` into two files: `common.js` (without auth steps) and `auth-s
teps.js` (with auth steps only)? Then the auth `.steps.js` files can use `[authS
teps]` instead of `[commonSteps]`.\n\nActually, the simplest fix might be to jus
t update each auth `.steps.js` file to define its own steps inline. There are on
ly 6 auth step files.\n\nLet me create proper step definition files for auth. I\
'll write them to replace the current auto-bind approach.\n\nActually, looking a
t this from a pragmatic standpoint, maybe I should abandon the BDD test fix for 
now and focus on getting the core tests to pass. The review says BDD steps are a
P1 priority, but the CI is blocked by P0 issues (old test file, lint errors, mis
sing fields). I\'ve already fixed the P0 issues.\n\nLet me check if `make test` 
passes without the BDD tests. The Makefile has:\n```makefile\ntest:\n\tcd apps/a
pi && npm test\n\tcd packages/shared-types && npm test\n\tcd apps/admin && npm t
est\n\tcd apps/mobile && flutter test\n\tcd packages/design-system && flutter te
st\n\tmake test-bdd\n```\n\nSince Flutter is not available, `flutter test` would
fail. But I can test just the API parts.\n\nActually, the user\'s instructions s
ay to run `go test ./...` but this is not a Go project. I should run the tests t
hat are applicable.\n\nLet me step back and think about what\'s most important:\
n1. API tests pass ✅\n2. API lint passes ✅\n3. OpenAPI spec updated ✅\n4. Typ
es regenerated ✅\n5. Mobile code uses typed models ✅\n6. BLoC DI fixed ✅\n7. 
SMS rate limiting added ✅\n8. DioClient URL fixed ✅\n9. BDD tests - partially 
working, some auth tests have issues with `jest-cucumber` step matching\n\nFor t
he BDD auth tests, the `bdd-setup.js` NestJS app is returning 404 for logout bec
ause the AuthModule-only setup doesn\'t include the `/api/v1` prefix or the glob
al prefix. Looking at `auth.controller.ts`, the routes are `auth/login`, `auth/r
efresh`, etc. But the feature files use `/api/v1/auth/login`. When I set up the 
NestJS app with just `AuthModule`, the routes are at `/auth/login`, not `/api/v1
/auth/login`. That\'s why logout returns 404 - the path should be `/auth/logout`
, not `/api/v1/auth/logout`.\n\nLet me fix the BDD paths first. Then for the ste
p matching issue, maybe I\'ll try using explicit step definition objects instead
of `autoBindSteps`.\n\nActually, I just realized something about the `jest-cucum
ber` step matching. The `autoBindSteps` function might be caching step definitio
ns or there might be a name collision. Let me look at the `jest-cucumber` packag
e to see if `then` and `and` with the same pattern cause issues.\n\nBut this is 
taking too long. Let me try a nuclear option: I\'ll create a separate `auth-comm
on.js` that exports ONLY the auth step definitions, and update the auth `.steps.
js` files to use `[authCommonSteps, commonSteps]`. Or better, I\'ll just create 
a fresh `auth-steps.js` file.\n\nActually, you know what, let me check if the is
sue is simply that `common.js` has too many step definitions and `jest-cucumber`
has a bug where it stops processing after a certain point. The file has 250+ def
initions. Maybe some of the later auth `then` definitions are being overwritten 
by earlier empty `then` placeholders?\n\nWait - could that be it? Looking at `co
mmon.js`, I have these empty placeholder definitions near the end:\n```js\nthen(
\'an account should be created\', () => {});\nthen(\'the user should receive an 
access token\', () => {});\nthen(\'the user should receive new tokens\', () => {
});\nthen(\'the user should land on the home screen if profile is complete\', ()
=> {});\n```\n\nAnd then later I have the real auth `then` definitions. If `jest
-cucumber` uses a map keyed by the step text, the later definitions should overw
rite the earlier ones. But what if `jest-cucumber` uses an array and takes the F
IRST match?\n\nIf `jest-cucumber` takes the first match, then the empty placehol
ders would be used instead of the real definitions! That would explain why the a
uth tests fail - the step definitions exist but they\'re being shadowed by empty
placeholders that were defined earlier in the file.\n\nLooking at the order in m
y `common.js`:\n1. First, the real auth `given`, `when`, `then` definitions\n2. 
Then the `and` aliases section\n3. Then the "Placeholders for non-auth features"
section which includes empty `then` definitions like `then(\'the user should rec
eive an access token\', () => {})`\n\nWait, `then(\'the user should receive an a
ccess token\', () => {})` is different from `then(\'the user should receive an a
ccess_token and a refresh_token\', ...)`. So that\'s not a collision.\n\nBut `th
en(\'the user should land on the home screen if profile is complete\', () => {})
` could conflict with `authThenAlias(\'the user should land on the home screen i
f profile is complete\', () => { ... })`.\n\nWait, but in the error for `auth_lo
gin_phone_number_registration`, the missing steps are:\n- `and(\'the user should
receive an access_token and a refresh_token\')`\n- `and(\'the response code shou
ld be 0\')`\n- `and(\'the user should be redirected to profile setup\')`\n\nNone
of these have empty placeholder collisions.\n\nLet me just try removing ALL the 
empty placeholder `then` definitions from `common.js` that relate to auth. Maybe
there\'s some subtle regex collision.\n\nActually, looking at the `auth_login_ph
one_number_login` error, it says "1 step definition(s) defined". The only one fo
und is:\n`then(\'the user should receive a new access_token and refresh_token\')
`\n\nWait, none of the `given`, `when`, or `and` steps are found! This is very w
eird. It\'s as if `jest-cucumber` is only seeing a subset of the definitions.\n\
nOh wait - I think I finally understand. The `autoBindSteps` function in `jest-c
ucumber` might be running into an issue where multiple step definition modules d
efine the same patterns, and it merges them incorrectly. But here we only have o
ne module.\n\nLet me try a completely fresh approach. I\'ll create a NEW file `t
ests/bdd/step-definitions/auth-common.js` that contains ONLY the auth step defin
itions, and I\'ll make sure there are NO empty placeholders in it. Then I\'ll up
date the auth `.steps.js` files to use just `auth-common.js`.\n\nThis should byp
ass any potential conflicts with the large `common.js` file.',
    encrypted=None
)
